SIMPLE: meretricious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Meretricious
<hw>Mer`e*tri"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>meretricius</ets>, from <ets>meretrix</ets>, <ets>-icis</ets>, a
prostitute, lit., one who earns money, <it>i. e.</it>, by prostitution,
fr. <ets>merere</ets> to earn, gain. See <er>Merit</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to prostitutes; having to do with
harlots; lustful; <as>as, <ex>meretricious</ex> traffic</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Resembling the arts of a harlot; alluring by false
show; gaudily and deceitfully ornamental; tawdry; <as>as,
<ex>meretricious</ex> dress or ornaments</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Deceptive or based on deception; seeming plausible,
but based on pretense or insincerity; deceptive; misleading; insincere;
specious; <as>as, <ex>meretricious</ex> arguments</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mer`e*tri"cious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Mer`e*tri"cious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meretriciousness</ent>⟦br⟧
